From: Venkatesh Prasad Ranganath <rvprasad@ksu.edu>
To: Michael Ernst <mernst@csail.mit.edu>
Cc: indus-developers@lists.projects.cis.ksu.edu
Subject: Re: [Indus-developers] How can I use the Indus slicer
	programmatically?
Date: Fri, 26 May 2006 15:08:06 -0500

Hi Mike,

First off, Indus does not (yet) directly operate on Java programs.  So,
you will need to compile your program into bytecodes and then into
Jimple (as supported by Soot 2.1.0).

The Jimple representation of your program is given below.

IndusSlicerTest

  <IndusSlicerTest: void main(java.lang.String[])>:
      > r0 : java.lang.String[]
      > $r1 : java.util.Random
      > i0 : int
      > i1 : int
      > $i2 : int
      > $i3 : int
      > i4 : int
      0: r0 := @parameter0: java.lang.String[]
      1: $r1 = new java.util.Random
      2: specialinvoke $r1.<java.util.Random: void <init>()>()
      3: $i2 = virtualinvoke $r1.<java.util.Random: int nextInt()>()
      4: $i3 = 1 + $i2
      5: i0 = $i3
      6: i1 = $i3
      7: if i1 != 2 goto i0 = 20
      8: i1 = 10
      9: goto [?= i4 = i1 + i0]
      10: i0 = 20
      11: i4 = i1 + i0
      12: return
    Traps: 

Given the above Jimple representation, to programmatically generate a
slice
 - use SliceCriteriaFactory to create criteria based on either a Value
object (denotes an expression), a Stmt object, or a SootMethod object of
interest, 
 - initialize the slicer as done in SliceXMLizerCLI, and
 - execute the slicer with the above criteria (via addCriteria()
method).
Examples.zip contains illustrative examples of how to programmatically
use various analysis (including the slicer) in Indus.

As for command line, please use SliceXMLizerCLI class provided in
examples.zip (and bundled in slicer.jar).  This CLI provides numerous
options to configure and execute the slicer from the command line.  One
such option is to provide the slice criteria in a serialized form as an
XML document.  Please refer to sliceCriteria.xsd and criteria.xml
(available in slicer.jar) for detailed information about the
syntax/semantics of the criteria XML document.

I hope that helps; if not, please post your
questions/concerns/suggestions on the mailing list or on the public
forums (preferable).

Thanks for your interest in Indus!

-- 

Venkatesh Prasad Ranganath,
Dept. Computing and Information Science,
Kansas State University, US.
web: http://www.cis.ksu.edu/~rvprasad

